<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-18T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-18T19:00:00-05:00" n="239" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d239">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">841.731/2122: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-18T19:00:00-05:00">October 18, 1939—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1245. Department’s 1238, October 17, 8 p.m. Acme Code Company anxious
                                to have their code included in the list of permissible codes
                                referred to in your 2050, October 16, 1 p.m. French administration
                                has included Acme in their list of permissible codes. Unless you
                                perceive objection to such a course, please ascertain whether
                                British would be willing to include Acme in codes permitted in
                                telegraphic messages between United States and Great Britain.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>